<h2><span><span class="conr">#1</span> <a href="viewtopic.php?pid=2291#p2291">2017-07-01 15:59:33</a></span></h2>
<div class="box">
<div class="inbox">
<div class="postbody">
<div class="postleft">
<dl>
<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=9398">zilogp112</a></strong></dt>
<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Unconfirmed Member</strong></dd>
<dd><span>Registered: 2017-06-28</span></dd>
<dd><span>Posts: 1</span></dd>
</dl>
</div>
<div class="postright">
<h3>How to perform efficient debugging of ACPI code compromising Linux</h3>
<div class="postmsg">
<p>Hello,</p><p>assuming there is ACPI code, whose execution by the Linux kernel results in compromising the system: It&#039;s one thing to analyze the details of how the system is compromised (which can be done using the Volatility Framework, Cuckoo sandbox or by using other methods). However, it&#039;s another issue, and much more difficult, to analyze how the ACPI code&#039;s execution led to the system getting compromised.</p><p>Is there anyone having experience with doing so? One can read on blackhat.com e. g. that ACPI-based rootkits are able to do so, but the presentations I found there and elsewhere don&#039;t focus much on the analysis process (how it has been performed) itself but rather on the results.</p><p>I guess that there is no other way than performing extensive kernel debugging for this purpose, and that the building of a custom kernel which includes appropriate debugging features would be necessary as well.</p><p>Among other material I found this as a &#039;starting point&#039; for performing this kind of analysis:<br/>https://01.org/linux-acpi/documentation/debug-how-isolate-linux-acpi-issues</p><p>However, I don&#039;t believe that setting the kernel&#039;s ACPI debug level to maximum would be sufficient at all in most cases. Does anyone have an advice in this regard, e. g. on how one should configure a custom kernel to use the debugging features in the most efficient way?</p><br/><p>Kind regards and thanks in advance</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
